VALUES
(43, 13, 1, 43, 12, 23, 23, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Hour', 'Both passages emphasize the arrival of ''the hour'' for Jesus. In John 12:23, Jesus indicates that this hour is for his glorification, while John 13:1 reflects on the culmination of his mission and love for his followers as that hour approaches.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 1, 43, 13, 34, 34, 'he loved them unto the end', 'Connection of Love Commandment', 'This connection highlights the theme of love, as both passages emphasize Jesus'' love for his own and the command to love one another. The phrase ''he loved them unto the end'' reflects the depth of love that is to be mirrored in the commandment given in the second passage.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 1, 62, 4, 19, 19, 'having loved his own which were in the world', 'Connection of Divine Love', 'This connection highlights the theme of love, where Jesus'' love for his own is emphasized in John 13:1, and 1 John 4:19 states that we love because he first loved us. Both passages emphasize the initiative of divine love as foundational to our response.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 1, 46, 1, 8, 8, 'loved them unto the end', 'Love and Endurance in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of enduring love and support. Both passages emphasize the idea of being loved and confirmed ''unto the end,'' suggesting a continuity of divine care and assurance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 1, 49, 5, 25, 26, 'loved his own which were in the world', 'Love and Sacrifice Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of love and self-giving. Both passages emphasize the depth of love, with Jesus loving his own ''unto the end'' and husbands called to love their wives as Christ loved the church.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 1, 66, 1, 5, 5, 'having loved his own which were in the world', 'Connection of Love and Redemption', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' love for his followers. In John, he loves them ''unto the end,'' while in Revelation, he loves us and ''washed us from our sins.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 1, 40, 26, 45, 45, 'his hour was come', 'Connection of Jesus'' Hour', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' impending hour. Both passages emphasize the significance of this hour in relation to his betrayal and departure.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 2, 59, 1, 13, 17, NULL, 'Temptation and Betrayal Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of temptation, as both passages address how individuals are drawn into sin. In John 13:2, Judas is influenced by the devil to betray Jesus, while James 1:14 explains that temptation arises from one''s own desires.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 2, 44, 5, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Betrayal and Deception', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and deception influenced by Satan. Both passages emphasize how Satan fills the hearts of individuals to lead them into wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 2, 15, 7, 27, 27, 'put into the heart', 'Divine Influence on Hearts', 'This connection highlights how both passages emphasize the theme of God or the devil influencing the hearts of individuals. In John 13:2, the devil puts betrayal in Judas''s heart, while Ezra 7:27 shows God putting a good purpose in the king''s heart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 2, 16, 2, 12, 12, 'put into the heart', 'Divine Influence on Hearts', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine influence on the hearts of individuals. In John 13:2, the devil puts a thought into Judas''s heart, while in Nehemiah 2:12, God puts a purpose into Nehemiah''s heart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 2, 42, 22, 3, 3, 'the devil having now put into the heart', 'Connection of Judas''s Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize the influence of Satan on Judas Iscariot, indicating a direct connection between his betrayal of Jesus. The mention of Satan''s involvement in both verses highlights the spiritual conflict surrounding Judas''s actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 2, 42, 22, 31, 31, 'the devil having now put into the heart', 'Betrayal and Spiritual Conflict', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and spiritual conflict. In both passages, the influence of Satan is evident, with Judas being prompted to betray Jesus and Peter warned of being sifted by Satan.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 2, 43, 6, 70, 71, NULL, 'Connection of Judas Iscariot''s Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize Judas Iscariot''s role as a betrayer. The first passage indicates the devil''s influence on Judas, while the second identifies him explicitly as ''one of you is a devil.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 3, 43, 3, 35, 35, 'given all things into his hands', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize that the Father has given all things into the Son''s hand, highlighting the authority and relationship between them. This connection underscores the divine empowerment of Jesus as recognized in both verses.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 3, 40, 11, 27, 27, 'the Father had given all things into his hands', 'Authority of the Son', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus as given by the Father. John 13:3 states that ''the Father had given all things into his hands,'' while Matthew 11:27 mentions ''All things are delivered unto me of my Father.''', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 3, 58, 1, 2, 2, 'all things into his hands', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus as the one appointed heir of all things. John highlights that all things were given into Jesus'' hands, while Hebrews states he is appointed heir of all things.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 3, 40, 28, 18, 18, 'all things into his hands', 'Authority of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the authority given to Jesus. In John 13:3, it states that ''all things'' were given into his hands, while Matthew 28:18 declares that ''All power is given unto me.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 3, 43, 8, 42, 42, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Origin', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' divine origin and mission. In John 13:3, Jesus acknowledges that he ''came from God,'' which parallels John 8:42 where he states he ''proceeded forth and came from God.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 3, 46, 15, 27, 27, 'all things into his hands', 'Authority of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' authority over all things. In John 13:3, it states that ''the Father had given all things into his hands,'' which parallels 1 Corinthians 15:27, where it mentions that ''all things are put under him.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 3, 49, 1, 21, 22, 'all things into his hands', 'Authority and Supremacy of Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' authority. Both passages emphasize that all things are given to Jesus, establishing his supremacy over all powers and dominions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 4, 42, 22, 27, 27, 'girded himself', 'Servanthood in Jesus'' Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood. In John 13:4, Jesus demonstrates humility by girding himself with a towel, while Luke 22:27 emphasizes his role as a servant among his disciples.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 4, 47, 8, 9, 9, 'laid aside his garments', 'Service and Sacrifice Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility and service in Jesus'' actions. In John 13:4, Jesus lays aside his garments to serve, while 2 Corinthians 8:9 emphasizes his choice to become poor for others'' benefit.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 4, 42, 12, 37, 37, 'girded himself', 'Servanthood and Readiness', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood, as both passages depict the act of girding oneself in preparation for service. In John, Jesus girds himself to serve his disciples, while in Luke, the lord girds himself to serve his faithful servants. Both emphasize the importance of readiness and humility in service.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 4, 50, 2, 6, 8, 'laid aside his garments', 'Humility and Servanthood', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility and servanthood in both passages. In John 13:4, Jesus demonstrates his servanthood by laying aside his garments and girding himself with a towel, while Philippians 2:7 emphasizes that he took upon him the form of a servant.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 4, 42, 17, 7, 7, 'laid aside his garments', 'Servanthood and Humility', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood, as both passages depict actions related to serving others. In John, Jesus demonstrates humility by girding himself with a towel, while in Luke, the expectation of a servant''s duty is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 5, 42, 7, 44, 44, 'wash the disciples’ feet', 'Washing of Feet Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of washing feet, highlighting its significance in hospitality and humility. In John, Jesus washes the disciples'' feet, while in Luke, a woman washes Jesus'' feet with her tears, contrasting the lack of hospitality shown by Simon.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 5, 19, 51, 2, 2, 'wash', 'Cleansing and Washing Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the act of washing as a means of cleansing. John 13:5 illustrates a physical washing, while Psalms 51:2 speaks to a spiritual cleansing from sin.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 5, 54, 5, 10, 10, NULL, 'Service and Humility in Action', 'This connection highlights the act of washing feet as a symbol of service and humility. Both passages emphasize the importance of serving others, with John 13:5 depicting Jesus washing the disciples'' feet and 1 Timothy 5:10 mentioning the washing of the saints'' feet as a commendable act.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 5, 1, 18, 4, 4, NULL, 'Washing Feet Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of washing feet, highlighting a theme of humility and service. In John, Jesus performs this act for his disciples, while in Genesis, it is offered as a gesture of hospitality.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 5, 1, 19, 2, 2, NULL, 'Washing Feet as Service', 'This connection highlights the act of washing feet as a symbol of humility and service in both passages. In John 13:5, Jesus washes the disciples'' feet, while in Genesis 19:2, the act of washing feet is offered as a sign of hospitality.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 5, 3, 14, 8, 8, NULL, 'Cleansing and Purification Rituals', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing through water in both passages. In John 13:5, the act of washing signifies a spiritual cleansing, while Leviticus 14:8 describes a physical cleansing ritual involving water.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 5, 9, 25, 41, 41, NULL, 'Servanthood and Humility', 'Both passages emphasize the act of washing feet as a symbol of servanthood and humility. In John, Jesus washes the disciples'' feet, while in 1 Samuel, the woman offers to wash the feet of the servants, highlighting the importance of serving others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 6, 40, 3, 11, 14, 'dost thou wash my feet?', 'Humility in Service', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility in both passages. Peter''s question, ''dost thou wash my feet?'' reflects his unworthiness, similar to John''s statement, ''I have need to be baptized of thee.'' Both express a recognition of the greater authority of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 6, 43, 1, 27, 27, 'dost thou wash my feet', 'Humility and Worthiness', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility in both passages. Peter''s question about washing feet reflects his sense of unworthiness, similar to John the Baptist''s acknowledgment of not being worthy to unloose Jesus'' shoe''s latchet.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 6, 42, 5, 8, 8, NULL, 'Peter''s Recognition of Sinfulness', 'This connection highlights Peter''s awareness of his own unworthiness in the presence of Jesus. In both passages, Peter expresses a sense of humility and recognition of his sinful nature when confronted by Jesus'' actions.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 7, 27, 12, 8, 8, 'thou shalt know hereafter', 'Understanding Divine Mysteries', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of understanding regarding divine matters. In John, Jesus indicates that knowledge will come later, while in Daniel, the speaker expresses confusion about future events.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 7, 43, 12, 16, 16, 'thou shalt know hereafter', 'Understanding After Glorification', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding that develops over time. In both passages, the disciples initially lack comprehension but later gain insight after Jesus'' glorification.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 7, 43, 14, 26, 26, 'thou shalt know hereafter', 'Teaching and Remembrance Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding and remembrance in the disciples'' relationship with Jesus. In John 13:7, Jesus indicates that the disciples will gain understanding in the future, while John 14:26 emphasizes that the Holy Spirit will teach and remind them of Jesus'' words.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 7, 59, 5, 7, 11, 'thou shalt know hereafter', 'Patience and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of patience in both passages. In John 13:7, Jesus indicates that understanding will come later, while James 5:7-11 encourages believers to be patient as they await the Lord''s coming.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 7, 35, 2, 1, 3, 'thou shalt know hereafter', 'Understanding Divine Timing', 'This connection highlights the theme of waiting for understanding. Both passages emphasize that knowledge or vision will be revealed in due time, encouraging patience in the face of uncertainty.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 7, 24, 32, 24, 25, 'thou shalt know hereafter', 'Understanding Divine Timing', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding events in God''s timing. In John 13:7, Jesus indicates that knowledge will come in the future, paralleling Jeremiah 32:24-25, where the fulfillment of prophecy is acknowledged as it unfolds.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 7, 24, 32, 43, 43, 'thou shalt know hereafter', 'Understanding Future Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of future understanding in both passages. In John 13:7, Jesus indicates that knowledge will come later, while Jeremiah 32:43 speaks of future actions in a land perceived as desolate, suggesting a time when understanding and restoration will occur.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 8, 26, 36, 25, 25, 'wash thee not, thou hast no part', 'Cleansing and Participation', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing in both passages. In John 13:8, Jesus emphasizes the necessity of being washed to have a part with Him, while Ezekiel 36:25 speaks of being cleansed from filthiness. Both verses underscore the importance of purification for a relationship with the divine.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 8, 44, 22, 16, 16, NULL, 'Washing and Cleansing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of washing as a means of purification. In John 13:8, Jesus emphasizes the necessity of washing for a relationship with Him, while Acts 22:16 speaks of baptism as a way to wash away sins.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 8, 56, 3, 5, 5, NULL, 'Washing and Salvation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of washing as essential for participation in the community of believers. Both passages emphasize the necessity of a spiritual cleansing, with John focusing on Jesus'' act of washing and Titus on the washing of regeneration.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 8, 49, 5, 26, 26, 'wash thee not', 'Washing and Cleansing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing through washing. In John 13:8, the act of washing signifies a necessary purification for fellowship with Jesus, while Ephesians 5:26 speaks of cleansing through the washing of water, indicating a spiritual renewal.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 8, 58, 10, 22, 22, NULL, 'Washing and Cleansing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of washing as a means of purification and relationship with Jesus. In John, Jesus emphasizes the necessity of being washed to have a part with Him, while Hebrews speaks of being washed with pure water as a preparation to draw near to God.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 8, 46, 6, 11, 11, NULL, 'Washing and Spiritual Cleansing', 'This connection highlights the theme of washing as essential for belonging to Jesus. In John 13:8, Jesus emphasizes the necessity of being washed to have a part with Him, while 1 Corinthians 6:11 speaks of being washed as part of the process of sanctification and justification.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 8, 38, 13, 1, 1, 'thou hast no part with me', 'Connection of Cleansing and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing from sin and uncleanness. In John 13:8, the act of washing signifies a necessary purification to be part of Jesus, while Zechariah 13:1 speaks of a fountain for cleansing from sin.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 9, 19, 51, 2, 2, NULL, 'Cleansing and Purification Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the need for cleansing. John 13:9 reflects Peter''s desire for complete washing, while Psalms 51:2 requests thorough cleansing from sin.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 9, 60, 3, 21, 21, 'not my feet only, but also my hands and my head', 'Connection of Cleansing and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing and salvation. In John 13:9, Peter expresses a desire for complete cleansing, while 1 Peter 3:21 discusses baptism as a means of salvation and a good conscience toward God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 9, 19, 26, 6, 6, 'my hands', 'Washing Hands and Purity', 'Both passages emphasize the act of washing as a symbol of purity and innocence. Peter''s desire to wash not just his feet but also his hands connects to the psalmist''s declaration of washing hands in innocency.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 9, 58, 10, 22, 22, 'not my feet only, but also my hands and my head', 'Cleansing and Purity', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing, as Peter desires to be fully washed, while Hebrews speaks of bodies being washed with pure water. Both passages emphasize the importance of purification in approaching God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 9, 24, 4, 14, 14, NULL, 'Cleansing and Purification Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing, as both passages emphasize the need for purification—Peter desires to be fully cleansed, while Jeremiah calls for the washing of the heart from wickedness. Both reflect a deeper need for spiritual renewal.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 9, 40, 27, 24, 24, 'my hands', 'Washing of Hands Motif', 'This connection highlights the act of washing as a significant theme in both passages. In John 13:9, Peter expresses a desire for his entire body to be cleansed, while in Matthew 27:24, Pilate washes his hands to signify his innocence, linking the concept of purification and accountability.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 10, 43, 15, 3, 3, 'ye are clean', 'Connection of Cleansing Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''clean.'' In John 13:10, Jesus indicates that the disciples are clean, while in John 15:3, he states they are clean through his word, linking the idea of spiritual cleanliness to his teachings.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 10, 47, 7, 1, 1, 'clean every whit', 'Cleansing and Holiness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the need for cleansing, with John highlighting the necessity of washing feet to maintain cleanliness, while 2 Corinthians calls for cleansing from filthiness to perfect holiness. This connection highlights the theme of spiritual cleanliness and the pursuit of holiness.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 10, 47, 5, 17, 17, 'ye are clean', 'Cleanliness and New Creation', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''clean'' in both passages. In John 13:10, Jesus speaks of being clean, while 2 Corinthians 5:17 emphasizes becoming a new creature, suggesting a transformation that aligns with spiritual cleanliness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 10, 4, 19, 19, 21, 'ye are clean, but not all', 'Purity and Cleanness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''clean'' and the necessity of purification. John 13:10 reflects the idea of being clean after washing, while Numbers 19:19-21 outlines the process of purification for the unclean.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 10, 49, 5, 26, 27, 'is clean every whit', 'Cleansing and Purity Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of cleansing, with John highlighting the need for washing to maintain purity and Ephesians discussing the sanctification of the church through the washing of water. This connection highlights the importance of being clean and without blemish in the context of spiritual purity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 10, 3, 17, 15, 16, 'is clean every whit', 'Cleansing and Purity Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleanliness and the necessity of washing for purity. Both passages emphasize the importance of being clean, whether through physical washing or spiritual readiness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 10, 4, 19, 12, 13, 'is clean every whit', 'Purification and Cleanliness', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleanliness and purification in both passages. John 13:10 discusses the need for washing feet after being made clean, while Numbers 19:12-13 emphasizes the importance of purification to maintain cleanliness before God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 11, 43, 13, 18, 18, 'Ye are not all clean', 'Connection of Betrayal and Purity', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal present in both passages. John 13:11 indicates that not all are clean, while John 13:18 explicitly mentions betrayal by one who shares bread, linking the concepts of purity and treachery.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 11, 40, 26, 24, 25, 'Ye are not all clean', 'Connection of Betrayal and Cleanliness', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal present in both passages. John 13:11 indicates that not all are clean, referring to Judas, while Matthew 26:24-25 directly addresses Judas''s betrayal, emphasizing the gravity of his actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 11, 43, 2, 25, 25, 'he knew who should betray him', 'Knowledge of Betrayal and Humanity', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' profound understanding of human nature. In John 13:11, He knows who will betray Him, while in John 2:25, it states He knew what was in man.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 11, 43, 6, 64, 71, 'who should betray him', 'Connection of Betrayal and Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' foreknowledge of betrayal. In John 13:11, he states, ''Ye are not all clean,'' indicating awareness of Judas'' impending betrayal, which is further elaborated in John 6:64-71, where he identifies Judas as ''one of you is a devil.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 11, 43, 17, 12, 12, 'Ye are not all clean', 'Betrayal and Loss Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of betrayal and the fate of the betrayer. In John 13:11, the phrase ''Ye are not all clean'' indicates the presence of betrayal, while John 17:12 identifies ''the son of perdition'' as the one lost among them.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 12, 43, 13, 7, 7, 'Know ye what I have done to you?', 'Understanding Jesus'' Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of understanding Jesus'' actions. In John 13:7, Jesus indicates that the disciples do not yet comprehend the significance of his actions, while John 13:12 invites them to reflect on what he has done.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 12, 26, 24, 24, 24, 'Know ye what I have done to you?', 'Significance of Actions', 'This connection highlights the importance of actions as a means of understanding divine authority. Both passages emphasize that through their actions, individuals can come to know God’s intentions and teachings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 12, 43, 13, 4, 4, NULL, 'Washing of Feet Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying aside garments, which signifies humility and service. The act of washing feet in John 13:12 directly follows the preparation described in John 13:4, illustrating the transition from preparation to action.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 12, 26, 24, 19, 19, 'Know ye what I have done to you?', 'Understanding Actions and Meanings', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning the significance of actions. In both passages, there is an emphasis on seeking understanding about what has been done, as seen in ''Know ye what I have done to you?'' and ''Wilt thou not tell us what these things are to us?''.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 12, 40, 13, 51, 51, 'Know ye what I have done to you?', 'Understanding Jesus'' Teachings', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding Jesus'' actions and teachings. In both passages, Jesus prompts his followers to reflect on their comprehension of what he has done and taught.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 12, 41, 4, 13, 13, 'Know ye what I have done to you?', 'Understanding Through Questions', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of understanding through questions posed by Jesus. In John, he asks if they know what he has done, while in Mark, he questions their understanding of parables.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 13, 42, 6, 46, 46, NULL, 'Authority and Obedience', 'This connection highlights the relationship between recognizing Jesus as Lord and the expectation of obedience to His teachings. Both passages emphasize the importance of acknowledging Jesus'' authority while also acting in accordance with His commands.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
